A complete, code-first guide to understanding how CSS actually decides which style wins — so you stop guessing and start controlling your styles.

Almost every developer learns CSS the same broken way: copy a class, tweak some values, and if it doesn’t work, add !important until it does. That approach works for a to-do list app. It falls apart the moment you're working on a real codebase with hundreds of stylesheets fighting each other.
This article rebuilds CSS from the ground up — what it actually is, how to include it, its exact syntax rules, and most importantly, the two concepts that explain every “why isn’t my CSS working” moment you’ll ever have: specificity and the cascade.

1. What Is CSS, Really?
CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a rule-based language that describes how HTML elements should look — colors, spacing, layout, fonts, animations — completely separate from the HTML that describes what the content is.
Think of it this way: HTML is the skeleton and organs of a webpage. CSS is the skin, clothes, and posture. The same HTML can look like a 2005 GeoCities page or a polished SaaS landing page, depending entirely on the CSS applied to it.
<!-- HTML: structure only -->
<p>Welcome to my website</p>/* CSS: presentation only */
p {
color: #2563eb;
font-size: 24px;
font-weight: bold;
}The separation of structure (HTML) from presentation (CSS) is not a style choice — it’s the entire design philosophy of the web platform. It’s why you can redesign an entire site by editing one CSS file, without touching a single line of HTML.

2. Three Ways to Include CSS
There are exactly three ways to attach CSS to HTML, and each has a distinct use case. Understanding when to use which is just as important as knowing the syntax.
2.1 Inline CSS
Written directly on an HTML element using the style attribute.
<p style="color: red; font-size: 18px;">This text is red and 18px.</p>When to use it: Almost never in production code. It’s useful for quick one-off testing, or when styles are generated dynamically by JavaScript (e.g., setting a progress bar’s width based on a calculated percentage).
Why to avoid it generally:

• It mixes structure and presentation, defeating the purpose of CSS.

• It cannot be reused across elements.

• It has the highest specificity of the three methods (explained in detail below), making it a nightmare to override later.
2.2 Internal CSS
Written inside a <style> tag in the <head> of the HTML document.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
body {
font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
background-color: #f9fafb;
}
h1 {
color: #1e40af;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Hello World</h1>
</body>
</html>When to use it: Single-page prototypes, HTML emails (where external stylesheets often aren’t supported by email clients), or quick demos.
Limitation: Styles only apply to that one HTML file — no reuse across multiple pages.
2.3 External CSS
Written in a separate .css file and linked using the <link> tag.
<!-- index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
<h1>Hello World</h1>
</body>
</html>/* styles.css */
body {
font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
background-color: #f9fafb;
}
h1 {
color: #1e40af;
}When to use it: Virtually every real-world project. It’s the industry standard because:

• One file can style unlimited HTML pages.

• The browser caches the file, so repeat visits load faster.

• It keeps your codebase clean and maintainable.
Rule of thumb: If you’re building anything beyond a single throwaway page, use external CSS. Full stop.

3. CSS Syntax — The Building Blocks
Every CSS rule follows the exact same anatomy:
selector {
property: value;
}p {
color: blue;
font-size: 16px;
}Breaking this down:
Part Example Meaning Selector p Which element(s) this rule targets Declaration block { ... } The set of style rules, wrapped in curly braces Property color What aspect you're styling Value blue How you want it styled Declaration color: blue; One property-value pair, ending in a semicolon
Common selector types
/* Element selector — targets all <p> tags */
p {
line-height: 1.6;
}/* Class selector — targets elements with class="highlight" */
.highlight {
background-color: yellow;
}/* ID selector — targets the single element with id="main-title" */
#main-title {
font-size: 32px;
}/* Attribute selector — targets inputs of type "email" */
input[type="email"] {
border: 1px solid #ccc;
}/* Descendant selector — targets <a> tags inside <nav> */
nav a {
text-decoration: none;
}/* Pseudo-class — targets links when hovered */
a:hover {
color: darkred;
}<p class="highlight">This paragraph has a highlighted background.</p>
<h1 id="main-title">Main Page Title</h1>
4. Specificity: How the Browser Decides Which Rule Wins
Here’s the scenario every developer eventually hits: you write a style, it doesn’t apply, and you have no idea why. Nine times out of ten, the answer is specificity.
Specificity is a scoring system. When multiple CSS rules target the same element, the browser calculates a “specificity score” for each rule, and the highest score wins — regardless of the order they were written in (with one exception, covered in the cascade section).
The specificity scoring system
Think of specificity as a four-column score: (inline, IDs, classes/attributes/pseudo-classes, elements)
Selector type Points Example Inline style 1000 style="color: red;" ID selector 100 #header Class, attribute, pseudo-class 10 .btn, [type="text"], :hover Element, pseudo-element 1 div, p, ::before Universal selector * 0 *
Worked example
<p id="intro" class="highlight text-large">Hello there</p>p {
color: blue; /* Specificity: 1 (element) */
}.highlight {
color: green; /* Specificity: 10 (class) */
}#intro {
color: purple; /* Specificity: 100 (ID) */
}p.text-large#intro {
color: orange; /* Specificity: 1 + 10 + 100 = 111 */
}Result: the text renders orange. Why? Because p.text-large#intro scores 111 — one element (p), one class (.text-large), and one ID (#intro) — beating every other rule, regardless of the order they appear in the stylesheet.
A more realistic clash
/* File: styles.css */.card .title {
color: black; /* Specificity: 0-0-2-0 → (0,0,2,0) */
}.sidebar .card .title {
color: red; /* Specificity: 0-0-3-0 → (0,0,3,0) — WINS */
}<div class="sidebar">
<div class="card">
<h2 class="title">Card Title</h2>
</div>
</div>Even though .card .title might appear later in the file, .sidebar .card .title wins because it has three class selectors instead of two. More specific selectors beat less specific ones, no matter the source order.
!important — the nuclear option
p {
color: blue !important; /* Overrides almost everything, regardless of specificity */
}!important overrides normal specificity rules entirely. It should be treated as a last resort — typically only for overriding third-party CSS you can't edit directly (like a widget library). Overusing it creates a specificity arms race where every future style needs its own !important to win, and the codebase becomes unmaintainable.

5. The Cascade: Specificity’s Partner in Crime
“Cascading” in CSS refers to the process the browser uses to resolve conflicting rules when specificity alone doesn’t decide the winner. The cascade works through three factors, checked in this exact order:
Step 1: Importance
!important declarations beat normal declarations, no matter what. (Covered above.)
Step 2: Specificity
If importance is tied, the browser compares specificity scores (also covered above).
Step 3: Source order
If specificity is also tied, the rule that appears last in the CSS wins.
.button {
background-color: blue;
}.button {
background-color: green; /* Same specificity — this wins because it's LAST */
}<button class="button">Click Me</button>Result: The button is green, purely because that rule was declared last in the file. This is the single most common cause of “I changed the CSS and nothing happened” bugs — a later, equally-specific rule is silently overriding an earlier one.
Putting it all together: a full decision tree
/* Rule A */
p {
color: blue;
}/* Rule B */
.text {
color: green;
}/* Rule C */
p.text {
color: purple;
}/* Rule D */
p.text {
color: orange !important;
}<p class="text">What color am I?</p>Walking through the cascade:

• Importance check: Rule D has !important → it wins immediately. No need to even check specificity or order.

• Result: The text is orange.
If Rule D didn’t exist, the browser would move to specificity: Rule C (p.text = 11 points) beats Rule A (1 point) and Rule B (10 points) → text would be purple.

6. Inheritance: The Quiet Fourth Player
One more concept that trips up beginners: some CSS properties inherit from parent to child elements automatically, without needing to be re-declared.
body {
color: #333;
font-family: Georgia, serif;
}<body>
<div>
<p>This paragraph inherits color and font-family from body.</p>
</div>
</body>The <p> never had color or font-family set directly — it inherited them from <body>. Text-related properties (color, font-family, font-size, line-height) typically inherit. Box-related properties (margin, padding, border, width) typically do not — otherwise every nested element would shrink or shift unpredictably.
You can force inheritance manually when needed:
.child {
border-color: inherit; /* Forces a normally non-inheriting property to inherit anyway */
}
7. Putting It All Into Practice: A Complete Example
Here’s a small real-world snippet that uses everything covered above — external CSS, multiple selector types, specificity in action, and inheritance.
<!-- index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
<div class="card">
<h2 class="card-title" id="featured-title">Featured Article</h2>
<p>This paragraph inherits the body's font styling.</p>
<button class="btn">Read More</button>
</div>
</body>
</html>/* styles.css *//* Inheritance base */
body {
font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif;
color: #1f2937;
}/* Element selector — specificity: 0-0-0-1 */
h2 {
font-weight: 400;
}/* Class selector — specificity: 0-0-1-0 */
.card-title {
color: #6b7280;
}/* ID selector — specificity: 0-1-0-0 — wins over both rules above */
#featured-title {
color: #dc2626;
font-weight: 700;
}.card {
border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
border-radius: 8px;
padding: 20px;
max-width: 400px;
}.btn {
background-color: #2563eb;
color: white;
padding: 8px 16px;
border: none;
border-radius: 4px;
cursor: pointer;
}.btn:hover {
background-color: #1d4ed8;
}What’s happening here:

• The <h2> gets styled by three competing rules — element, class, and ID selectors — and the ID wins (#featured-title, specificity 100) because IDs outrank both classes and elements.

• The <p> never gets a color or font-family rule directly, yet renders in dark gray Segoe UI — pure inheritance from body.

• The .btn:hover rule only activates on mouse hover, demonstrating a pseudo-class in action.

Closing Thoughts
Once specificity and the cascade actually click, CSS stops feeling like a black box that randomly ignores your styles. Every “why isn’t this working” moment reduces to the same three questions:

• Is there an !important somewhere overriding me?

• Does a more specific selector exist elsewhere?

• If specificity is tied, which rule comes later in the file?
Master those three questions, and you’ll debug CSS in seconds instead of minutes — and more importantly, you’ll start writing CSS that doesn’t fight itself in the first place.

